import java.util.*;

class Node {
  int data;
  Node next;
  public Node(int data, Node next){
      this.data = data;
      this.next = next;
  }
  public Node(int data){
      this.data = data;
      this.next = null;
  }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
      System.out.println("Hello, World!");
      Node a = new Node(10);
      System.out.println(a);
      System.out.println(a.data);
    }
}

This Java code defines a simple singly linked list Node class with two constructors and data/next fields. In the main method, it prints "Hello, World!", creates a Node object a with data 10 (its next is null by default), then prints the object reference a (memory address) and the value a.data (which is 10). The code demonstrates basic class definition, object instantiation, and field access in Java.
